and often earthy, these mostly one-act plays depict deceit, dissembling, reversed gender roles, and sudden upending of fortunes. With zest and humor, they portray henpecked husbands, supercilious and lustful monks, all-too-human sage kings, disgruntled officials, and overreaching young scholars. These plays provide a glimpse of Chinese daily life and mores even as they question or subvert the boundaries of social, moral, and political order.Each translation is preceded by a short introduction that describes the play’s author, context, formal qualities, and textual history. A Topsy-Turvy World offers a new view of a significant period in the development of the Chinese theatrical tradition and provides insight into the role of drama as cultural critique.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aChinese dramayMing dynasty, 1368-1644vTranslations into English. 0aChinese dramayQing dynasty, 1644-1912vTranslations into English. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Asian / Chinese.2bisacsh1 aAshmore, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChaoguan, Yang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHe, Yuming, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeng, Wang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIdema, Wilt L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIdema, Wilt, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKaixian, Li, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKile, S. E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKwa, Shiamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLi, Wai-yee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLi, Wai-yee, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/v